# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rf-filters
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The **Butterworth filter** is a type of signal processing filter designed to have a frequency response that is as flat as possible in the passband.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] It is also referred to as a **maximally flat magnitude filter**.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] It was first described in 1930 by the British engineer and physicist Stephen Butterworth in his paper entitled "On the Theory of Filter Amplifiers".
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth had a reputation for solving very complex mathematical problems thought to be 'impossible'.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] At the time, filter design required a considerable amount of designer experience due to limitations of the theory then in use.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The filter was not in common use for over 30 years after its publication.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Such an ideal filter cannot be achieved, but Butterworth showed that successively closer approximations were obtained with increasing numbers of filter elements of the right values.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] At the time, filters generated substantial ripple in the passband, and the choice of component values was highly interactive.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] where $\omega$ is the angular frequency in radians per second and n is the number of poles in the filter—equal to the number of reactive elements in a passive filter.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Its cutoff frequency (the half-power point of approximately −3 dB or a voltage gain of 1/√2 ≈ 0.7071) is normalized to 𝜔 = 1 radian per second.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth only dealt with filters with an even number of poles in his paper, though odd-order filters can be created with the addition of a single-pole filter applied to the output of the even-order filter.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] He built his higher-order filters from 2-pole filters separated by vacuum tube amplifiers.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] His plot of the frequency response of 2-, 4-, 6-, 8-, and 10-pole filters is shown as A, B, C, D, and E in his original graph.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth solved the equations for two-pole and four-pole filters, showing how the latter could be cascaded when separated by vacuum tube amplifiers and so enabling the construction of higher-order filters despite inductor losses.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] In 1930, low-loss core materials such as molypermalloy had not been discovered and air-cored audio inductors were rather lossy.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth discovered that it was possible to adjust the component values of the filter to compensate for the winding resistance of the inductors.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] He used coil forms of 1.25 inches (32 mm) in diameter and 3 inches (76 mm) in length with plug-in terminals.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Associated capacitors and resistors were contained inside the wound coil form.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The coil formed part of the plate load resistor.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Two poles were used per vacuum tube and RC coupling was used to the grid of the following tube.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth also showed that the basic low-pass filter could be modified to give low-pass, high-pass, band-pass and band-stop functionality.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The frequency response of the Butterworth filter is maximally flat (i.e., has no ripples) in the passband and rolls off towards zero in the stopband.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] When viewed on a logarithmic Bode plot, the response slopes off linearly towards negative infinity.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] A first-order filter's response rolls off at −6 dB per octave (−20 dB per decade) (all first-order lowpass filters have the same normalized frequency response).
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] A second-order filter decreases at −12 dB per octave, a third-order at −18 dB and so on.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth filters have a monotonically changing magnitude function with $\omega$ , unlike other filter types that have non-monotonic ripple in the passband or the stopband.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] A simple example of a Butterworth filter is the third-order low-pass design shown in the figure on the right, with $C_{2}$ = 4/3 F, $R_{4}$ = 1 Ω, $L_{1}$ = 3/2 H, and $L_{3}$ = 1/2 H.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The group delay is defined as the negative derivative of the phase shift with respect to angular frequency and is a measure of the distortion in the signal introduced by phase differences for different frequencies.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The gain and the delay for this filter are plotted in the graph on the left.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] There are no ripples in the gain curve in either the passband or the stopband.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The log of the absolute value of the transfer function $H(s)$ is plotted in complex frequency space in the second graph on the right.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The function is defined by the three poles in the left half of the complex frequency plane.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] These are arranged on a circle of radius unity, symmetrical about the real s axis.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The gain function will have three more poles on the right half-plane to complete the circle.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] By replacing each inductor with a capacitor and each capacitor with an inductor, a high-pass Butterworth filter is obtained.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] A band-pass Butterworth filter is obtained by placing a capacitor in series with each inductor and an inductor in parallel with each capacitor to form resonant circuits.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The value of each new component must be selected to resonate with the old component at the frequency of interest.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] A band-stop Butterworth filter is obtained by placing a capacitor in parallel with each inductor and an inductor in series with each capacitor to form resonant circuits.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The value of each new component must be selected to resonate with the old component at the frequency that is to be rejected.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Like all filters, the typical prototype is the low-pass filter, which can be modified into a high-pass filter, or placed in series with others to form band-pass and band-stop filters, and higher order versions of these.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] where n is the order of filter, $\omega _{c}$ is the cutoff frequency (approximately the −3 dB frequency), and $G_{0}$ is the DC gain (gain at zero frequency).
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] It can be seen that as n approaches infinity, the gain becomes a rectangle function and frequencies below $\omega _{c}$ will be passed with gain $G_{0}$ , while frequencies above $\omega _{c}$ will be suppressed.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] For smaller values of n , the cutoff will be less sharp.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] We wish to determine the transfer function $H(s)$ where $s=\sigma +j\omega$ (from Laplace transform).
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] then, with $s=j\omega$ , we have the frequency response of the Butterworth filter.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The n poles of this expression occur on a circle of radius $\omega _{c}$ at equally-spaced points, and symmetric around the negative real axis.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] For stability, the transfer function, $H(s)$ , is therefore chosen such that it contains only the poles in the negative real half-plane of s .
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] where $\textstyle {\prod }$ is the product of a sequence operator.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The denominator is a Butterworth polynomial in s .
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The Butterworth polynomials may be written in complex form as above, but are usually written with real coefficients by multiplying pole pairs that are complex conjugates, such as $s_{1}$ and $s_{n}$ .
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The polynomials are normalized by setting $\omega _{c}=1$ .
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Factors of Butterworth polynomials of order 1 through 10 are shown in the following table (to six decimal places).
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Factors of Butterworth polynomials of order 1 through 6 are shown in the following table (Exact).
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] where the Greek letter phi ( $\varphi$ or $\phi$ ) represents the golden ratio.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Transformation to other bandforms are also possible, see prototype filter.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] which is monotonically decreasing for all $\omega$ since the gain G is always positive.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The gain function of the Butterworth filter therefore has no ripple.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] In other words, all derivatives of the gain up to but not including the 2 n -th derivative are zero at $\omega =0$ , resulting in "maximal flatness".
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] If the requirement to be monotonic is limited to the passband only and ripples are allowed in the stopband, then it is possible to design a filter of the same order, such as the inverse Chebyshev filter, that is flatter in the passband than the "maximally flat" Butterworth.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] To design a Butterworth filter using the minimum required number of elements, the minimum order of the Butterworth filter may be calculated as follows.
