[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] are the stop band frequency and attenuation at that frequency in dB.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] is the minimum number of poles, the order of the filter.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The cutoff attenuation for Butterworth filters is usually defined to be −3.01 dB.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] If it is desired to use a different attenuation at the cutoff frequency, then the following factor may be applied to each pole, whereupon the poles will continue to lie on a circle, but the radius will no longer be unity.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The cutoff attenuation equation may be derived through algebraic manipulation of the Butterworth defining equation stated at the top of the page.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] is the relocated pole positioned to set the desired cutoff attenuation.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] 3.01 dB cutoff pole that lies on the unit circle.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] is the desired attenuation at the cutoff frequency in dB (1 dB, 10 dB, etc.).
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] is the number of poles, the order of the filter.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] There are several different filter topologies available to implement a linear analogue filter.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The most often used topology for a passive realisation is the Cauer topology, and the most often used topology for an active realisation is the Sallen–Key topology.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The Cauer topology uses passive components (shunt capacitors and series inductors) to implement a linear analog filter.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The Butterworth filter having a given transfer function can be realised using a Cauer 1-form.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The filter may start with a series inductor if desired, in which case the *Lk* are *k* odd and the *Ck* are *k* even.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] These formulae may usefully be combined by making both *Lk* and *Ck* equal to *gk*.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] That is, *gk* is the immittance divided by *s*.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] These formulae apply to a doubly terminated filter (that is, the source and load impedance are both equal to unity) with ωc = 1.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] This prototype filter can be scaled for other values of impedance and frequency.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Voltage driven filters must start with a series element and current driven filters must start with a shunt element.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] These forms are useful in the design of diplexers and multiplexers.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The Sallen–Key topology uses active and passive components (noninverting buffers, usually op amps, resistors, and capacitors) to implement a linear analog filter.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Each Sallen–Key stage implements a conjugate pair of poles; the overall filter is implemented by cascading all stages in series.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] If there is a real pole (in the case where n is odd), this must be implemented separately, usually as an RC circuit, and cascaded with the active stages.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] We wish the denominator to be one of the quadratic terms in a Butterworth polynomial.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] This leaves two undefined component values that may be chosen at will.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth lowpass filters with Sallen–Key topology of third and fourth order, using only one op amp, are described by Huelsman, and further single-amplifier Butterworth filters also of higher order are given by Jurišić et al.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Digital implementations of Butterworth and other filters are often based on the bilinear transform method or the matched Z-transform method, two different methods to discretize an analog filter design.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] In the case of all-pole filters such as the Butterworth, the matched Z-transform method is equivalent to the impulse invariance method.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] For higher orders, digital filters are sensitive to quantization errors, so they are often calculated as cascaded biquad sections, plus one first-order or third-order section for odd orders.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] Here is an image showing the gain of a discrete-time Butterworth filter next to other common filter types.
[src:rf-filters/butterworth-filter] The Butterworth filter rolls off more slowly around the cutoff frequency than the Chebyshev filter or the Elliptic filter, but without ripple.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Type I Chebyshev filters are the most common types of Chebyshev filters.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] where $\varepsilon$ is the ripple factor, $\omega _{0}$ is the cutoff frequency and $T_{n}$ is a Chebyshev polynomial of the n th order.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The passband exhibits equiripple behavior, with the ripple determined by the ripple factor $\varepsilon$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] In the passband, the Chebyshev polynomial alternates between -1 and 1 so the filter gain alternate between maxima at $G=1$ and minima at $G=1/{\sqrt {1+\varepsilon ^{2}}}$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] At the cutoff frequency $\omega _{0}$ the gain again has the value $1/{\sqrt {1+\varepsilon ^{2}}}$ but continues to drop into the stopband as the frequency increases.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] This behavior is shown in the diagram on the right.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The common practice of defining the cutoff frequency at −3 dB is usually not applied to Chebyshev filters; instead the cutoff is taken as the point at which the gain falls to the value of the ripple for the final time.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The order of a Chebyshev filter is equal to the number of reactive components (for example, inductors) needed to realize the filter using analog electronics.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] An even steeper roll-off can be obtained if ripple is allowed in the stopband, by allowing zeros on the $\omega$ -axis in the complex plane.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] While this produces near-infinite suppression at and near these zeros (limited by the quality factor of the components, parasitics, and related factors), overall suppression in the stopband is reduced.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The result is called an elliptic filter, also known as a Cauer filter.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] For simplicity, it is assumed that the cutoff frequency is equal to unity.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The poles $(\omega _{pm})$ of the gain function of the Chebyshev filter are the zeroes of the denominator of the gain function.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] where the multiple values of the arc cosine function are made explicit using the integer index m .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The above expression yields the poles of the gain G .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] For each complex pole, there is another which is the complex conjugate, and for each conjugate pair there are two more that are the negatives of the pair.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The transfer function must be stable, so that its poles are those of the gain that have negative real parts and therefore lie in the left half plane of complex frequency space.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] where $s_{pm}^{-}$ are only those poles of the gain with a negative sign in front of the real term, obtained from the above equation.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The gain and the group delay for a 5th-order type I Chebyshev filter with ε=0.5 are plotted in the graph on the left.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] But the ripples of group delay in its passband indicate that different frequency components have different delay, which along with the ripples of gain in its passband results in distortion of the waveform's shape.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] This is due to the physical inability to accommodate the even order Chebyshev reflection zeros that result in a scattering matrix S12 values that exceed the S12 value at $\omega =0$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The needed modification involves mapping each pole of the Chebyshev transfer function in a manner that maps the lowest frequency reflection zero to zero and the remaining poles as needed to maintain the equi-ripple pass band.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The lowest frequency reflection zero may be found from the Chebyshev Nodes, $\cos {\Bigl (}{\frac {\pi (n-1)}{2n}}{\Bigl )}$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The complete Chebyshev pole mapping function is shown below.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] P' is the mapped pole for the modified even order transfer function.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] "Left Half Plane" indicates to use the square root containing a negative real value.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] When complete, a replacement equi-ripple transfer function is created with reflection zero scattering matrix values for S12 of one and S11 of zero when implemented with equally terminated passive networks.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The illustration below shows an 8th order Chebyshev filter modified to support even order equally terminated passive networks by relocating the lowest frequency reflection zero from a finite frequency to 0 while maintaining an equi-ripple pass band frequency response.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The LC element value formulas in the Cauer topology are not applicable to the even order modified Chebyshev transfer function, and cannot be used.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] It is therefore necessary to calculate the LC values from traditional continued fractions of the impedance function, which may be derived from the reflection coefficient, which in turn may be derived from the transfer function.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] To design a Chebyshev filter using the minimum required number of elements, the minimum order of the Chebyshev filter may be calculated as follows.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The equations account for standard low pass Chebyshev filters, only.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Even order modifications and finite stop band transmission zeros will introduce error that the equations do not account for.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] n is the minimum number of poles, the order of the filter.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Pass band cutoff attenuation for Chebyshev filters is usually the same as the pass band ripple attenuation, set by the computation above.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] However, many applications such as diplexers and triplexers, require a cutoff attenuation of -3.0103 dB in order to obtain the needed reflections.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Other specialized applications may require other specific values for cutoff attenuation for various reasons.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] It is therefore useful to have a means available of setting the Chebyshev pass band cutoff attenuation independently of the pass band ripple attenuation, such as -1 dB, -10 dB, etc.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The cutoff attenuation may be set by frequency scaling the poles of the transfer function.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The scaling factor may be determined by direct algebraic manipulation of the defining Chebyshev filter function, $G_{n}(\omega )$ , including $\varepsilon$ and $T_{n}(\omega /\omega _{0})$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] $p_{A}$ is the relocated pole positioned to set the desired cutoff attenuation.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] $p_{1}$ is a ripple cutoff pole that lies on the oval.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] $\delta$ is the passband attenuation ripple in dB (.05 dB, 1 dB, etc.)).
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] n is the number of poles (the order of the filter).
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] A quick sanity check on the above equation using passband ripple attenuation for the passband cutoff attenuation $(\alpha =\delta )$ reveals that the pole adjustment will be 1.0 for this case, which is what is expected.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] For Chebyshev filters being designed with modified for even order pass band ripple for passive equally terminated filters, the attenuation frequency computation needs to include the even order adjustment by performing the even order adjustment operation on the computed attenuation frequency.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] This makes the even order adjustment arithmetic slightly simpler, since frequency can be treated as a real variable, in this case $((J\omega )^{2}{\text{ becomes }}-\omega ^{2})$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] $p_{1}$ is a ripple cutoff pole that has been modified for even order pass bands.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Also known as inverse Chebyshev filters, the Type II Chebyshev filter type is less common because it does not roll off as fast as Type I, and requires more components.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] It has no ripple in the passband, but does have equiripple in the stopband.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] and the smallest frequency at which this maximum is attained is the cutoff frequency $\omega _{o}$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] For a stopband attenuation of 5 dB, ε = 0.6801; for an attenuation of 10 dB, ε = 0.3333.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The frequency *f*0 = *ω*0/2*π* is the cutoff frequency.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The zeroes of the type II Chebyshev filter are therefore the inverse of the zeroes of the Chebyshev polynomial.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The transfer function is given by the poles in the left half plane of the gain function, and has the same zeroes but these zeroes are single rather than double zeroes.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The gain and the group delay for a fifth-order type II Chebyshev filter with ε=0.1 are plotted in the graph on the left.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] It can be seen that there are ripples in the gain in the stopband but not in the pass band.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Just like Chebyshev filter even order filters, the standard Chebyshev II even order filter cannot be implemented with equally terminated passive elements without the use of coupled coils, which may not be desirable or feasible.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] In the Chebyshev II case, this is due to finite attenuation of S12 in the stop band.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] However, even order Chebyshev II filters may be modified by translating the highest frequency finite transmission zero to infinity, while maintaining the equi-ripple functions of the Chebyshev II stop band.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] To do this translation, an even order modified Chebyshev function is used in place of the standard Chebyshev function to define the Chebyshev II poles needed to create the even order modified Chebyshev II transfer function.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Zeros are created using the roots of the even order modified Chebyshev polynomial, which are the even order modified Chebyshev nodes.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The illustration below shows an 8th order Inverse Chebyshev filter modified to support even order equally terminated passive networks by relocating the highest frequency transmission zero from a finite frequency to $\infty$ while maintaining an equi-ripple stop band frequency response.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] To design an Inverse Chebyshev filter using the minimum required number of elements, the minimum order of the Inverse Chebyshev filter may be calculated as follows.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The equations account for standard low pass Inverse Chebyshev filters, only.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Even order modifications will introduce error that the equations do not account for.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The equations is identical to that used for Chebyshev filter minimum order, with a slightly different variable definitions.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The standard cutoff attenuation as described is the same at the pass band ripple attenuation.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] However, just as in Chebyshev filters, it is useful to set the cutoff attenuation to a desired value, and for the same reasons.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Setting the Chebyshev II cutoff attenuation is the same as for Chebyshev cutoff attenuation, except the arithmetic attenuation and ripple entries are inverted in the equation and the poles and zeros are multiplied by the result, as opposed to divided by in the Chebyshev case..
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The same even order adjustment to the poles and zeros that was used for the Chebyshev even order modified cutoff attenuation may also be used for the Chebyshev II case, both the poles and zeros are multiplied by the result.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] A passive LC Chebyshev low-pass filter may be realized using a Cauer topology.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Gn+1 is the output termination impedance when the last element is a shunt capacitor, and the output termination admittance when the last element is a series inductor.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Note that for odd order Chebyshev the distinction for the last element is moot.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] where $\delta$ is the passband ripple in decibels.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The number $17.37$ is rounded from the exact value $40/\ln(10)$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The calculated *G**k* values may then be converted into shunt capacitors and series inductors as shown on the right, or they may be converted into series capacitors and shunt inductors.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Note that when G1 is a shunt capacitor or series inductor, G0 corresponds to the input resistance or conductance, respectively.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The same relationship holds for Gn+1 and Gn.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] The resulting circuit is a normalized low-pass filter.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Using frequency transformations and impedance scaling, the normalized low-pass filter may be transformed into high-pass, band-pass, and band-stop filters of any desired cutoff frequency or bandwidth.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] As with most analog filters, the Chebyshev may be converted to a digital (discrete-time) recursive form via the bilinear transform.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] However, as digital filters have a finite bandwidth, the response shape of the transformed Chebyshev is warped.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Alternatively, the Matched Z-transform method may be used, which does not warp the response.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p01] Chebyshev filters are sharper than the Butterworth filter; they are not as sharp as the elliptic one, but they show fewer ripples over the bandwidth.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Chebyshev filter design flexibility may be augmented by more advanced design methods documented in this section.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Transmission zeros may be inserted into the stop band to neutralize specific undesired frequencies or increase the cut-off attenuation, or may be inserted off-axis to obtain a more desirable group delay.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Asymmetric Chebyshev band pass filters may be created that contain differing number of poles on each side of the pass band to meet frequency asymmetric design requirements more efficiently.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The equi-ripple pass bands and that Chebyshev filters are known for may be restricted to a percentage of the pass band to meet design requirements more efficiently that only call for a portion of the pass band to be equi-ripple.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Chebyshev filters may be designed with arbitrarily placed finite transmission zeros in the stop band while retaining an equi-ripple pass band.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Stop band zeros along the $j\omega$ axis are generally used to eliminate unwanted frequencies.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Stop band zeros along the real axis or quadruplet stop band zeros in the complex plane may be used to modify the group delay to a more desirable shape.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The calculation of K(S) relies upon the following observed equality.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] for all $z_{i}=\infty$ , imaginary conjugate pairs, quadruplet conjugate pairs, or real opposing signed pairs.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Given the magnitude is always one in the pass band ( $0\leq \omega \leq 1$ ) the rational and irrational terms must vary between 0 and 1.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Therefore, if only the rational term is used to create the $K(s)$ characteristic function, an equi-ripple response is expected in the pass band, and characteristic poles (transmission zeros) are expected at all $s=z_{i}$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The design process for K(S) using the above expression is below.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Use the positive $M_{i}$ solution for real and imaginary $z_{i}$ pairs.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Use the positive real and conjugate imaginary $M_{i}$ solution for quadruplet complex $z_{i}$ pairs.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] $K(s)$ should be normalized such that $|K(s)|=1{\text{ at }}s=j$ , if needed.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The, "rational terms only" indicates to keep the rational part of the product, and to discard the irrational part.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The rational term may be obtained by manually performing the polynomial arithmetic, or with the short cut below which is a solution derived from polynomial arithmetic and uses binomial coefficients.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The algorithm is extremely efficient if the Binomial coefficients are implemented from a look-up table of pre-calculated values.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] When all M values are set to one, then $K(s)_{num}$ will be the standard Chebyshev equation, which is expected since the all transmission zeros are it $\infty$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Even order finite transmission zero Chebyshev filters have the same limitation as the all-pole case in that they cannot be constructed using equally terminated passive networks.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The same even order modification may be made to the even order characteristic polynomials, $K(s)$ , to make equally terminated passive network implementations possible.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] However, the even order modification will also move the finite transmission zeros slightly.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] This movement may be significantly mitigated by propositioning the transmission zeros with the inverse of the even order modification using the lowest Chebyshev node, $cos(\pi (N-1)/(2N))$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] To find the $G(s)$ transfer function, do the following.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] To obtain $G(s)$ from the left half plane, factor the numerator and denominator to obtain the roots.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Discard all roots from the right half plane of the denominator, half the repeated roots in the numerator, and rebuild $G(s)$ with the remaining roots.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] To confirm that the example $G(s)$ is correct, the plot of $G(s)$ along $j\omega$ is shown below with a pass band ripple of 1 dB, a cut off frequency of 1 rad/sec, and a stop band zero at 2 rad/sec.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Chebyshev band pass filters may be designed with a geometrically asymmetric frequency response by placing the desired number of transmission zeros at zero and infinity with the use of the more generalized form of the Chebyshev transmission zeros equation above, and shown below.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The $K(s)$ equations below consider a frequency normalized pass band from 1 to $\omega _{2}$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] If the number of transmission zeros at 0 is not the same as the number of transmission zeros at $\infty$ , the filter will be geometrically asymmetric.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The filter will also be asymmetric if finite transmission zeros are not place symmetrically about the geometric center frequency, which in this case is ${\sqrt {\omega _{2}}}$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] There is a restriction in that he filter must be net even order, that is the sum of all the poles must be even, to make the asymmetric $K(s)$ equation produce usable results.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Real and complex quadruplet transmission zeros may also be created using this technique and are useful to modify the group delay response, just as in the low pass case.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The derivation of the characteristic equation, $K(s)$ , to create an asymmetric Chebyshev band pass filter is shown below.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Design an asymmetric Chebyshev filter with 1dB pass band ripple from 1 to 2 rad/sec, one transmission zero at $\infty$ , and three transmission zeros at 0.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] By applying the numeral values to the equations above, the characteristic polynomials, $K(s)$ , may be calculated as follows.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Use the same process as in the low pass case to find $G(s)$ from $K(s)$ , using constant C to scale the magnitude.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] When reconstructing the denominator from the left half plane poles, it will be necessary to set the $G(s)$ magnitude such that the reflection zeros occur at 0dB.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] To do this, $G(s)$ should be scaled such that $|G(s)|$ = -1dB at the pass band corner frequencies, $s=j$ and $s=j2$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Once accomplished, the final transfer function for the designed asymmetric Chebyshev filter is shown below.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Evaluating $|G(s)|$ at s=j and at s=2j produces a value of -1dB in both cases, yielding an assurance that the example has been synthesized correctly.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Standard low pass Chebyshev filter design creates an equi-ripple pass band beginning from 0 rad/sec to a frequency normalized value of 1 rad/sec.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] However, some design requirements do not need an equi-ripple pass band at the low frequencies.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] A standard full-equi-ripple Chebyshev filter for this application would result in an over designed filter.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Constricting the equi-ripple to a defined percentage of the pass band creates a more efficient design, reducing the size of the filter and potentially eliminating one or two components, which is useful in maximizing board space efficiency and minimizing production costs for mass produced items.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Constricted pass band ripple can be achieved by designing an asymmetric Chebyshev band pass filter using the techniques described above in this article with a 0 order asymmetric high pass side (no transmission zeros at 0) and an $\omega 2$ set to the constricted ripple frequency.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The order of the low pass side is N-1 for odd order filters, N-2 for even order modified filters, and N for standard even order filters.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] This results in a less than unity S12 at $\omega =0$ , which is typical of even order standard Chebyshev design, so for standard even order Chebyshev designs, the process is complete at this step.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] It will be necessary to insert a single reflection zero at $\omega =0$ for odd order designs, and two reflection zeros at $\omega =0$ for even order modified designs.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Added reflection zeros introduces a noticeable error in the pass band that is likely to be objectionable.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] This error may be removed quickly and accurately by repositioning the finite reflection zeros with the use of Newton's method for systems of equations.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The value of the magnitude normalized $|K(j\omega )|$ , that is $|K(j)|=1$ , at the constriction frequency and at each minima above the constriction frequency.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The Jacobian matrix of partial derivative of $|K(j\omega )_{|K(j)|=1}|$ for the constriction frequency and at each minima above the constriction frequency. with respect to each reflection zero.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The roots of this polynomial will be the pass band minima frequencies. $(dK(s)/ds)_{num}$ is obtainable from standard polynomial derivative definitions, and is $(dK(s)/ds)num=K(s)_{den}(d(K(s)_{num})/ds)-K(s)_{num}(d(K(s)_{den})/ds)$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] To obtain the continuous partial derivatives of $|K(s)_{|K(j)|=1}|$ with respect to the reflections zeros, a continuous expression for $K(s)$ needs to be obtained that forces $|K(j)|=1$ at all times.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] This may be achieved by expressing $K(s)$ as a function of its conjugate root pairs, as shown below.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Where $K{finite}(s)$ includes finite reflection and transmission zeros, only, $N_{Rz}$ and $N_{Tz}$ refer to the number of reflection and transmission zero conjugate pairs, and $Rz_{i}$ and $Tz_{i}$ are the reflection and transmission zero conjugate pairs.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The s odd term accounts for the single reflection zero at 0 that occurs in odd order Chebyshev filters.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Note that if quadruplet transmission zeros are employed, the expression must be modified to accommodate quadruplet terms.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] It is seen by inspection that $|K(s)|=1$ whenever $s=j$ in the above expression.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Since only movement of the reflection zeros is needed to shape the Chebyshev pass band, the partial derivative expression only needs to be made on the $Rz_{i}$ terms, and the $Tz_{i}$ terms are treated as a constant.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] To aid in the determination of the partial derivative expression for each $Rz_{i}$ , the expression above may be rewritten, as shown below.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Where $Rz_{k}^{2}$ designates a specific reflection zero conjugate pair.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] This derivative of this expression with respect to $Rz_{k}$ may be easily computed following standard derivative rules.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The constant requires the dividing out of the $R_{k}^{2}$ terms to maintain the integrity of the function.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The easiest way to do this is to multiply $|K(j\omega )|$ by the inverse of the $R_{k}^{2}$ terms that were moved to the front.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The differentiable expression may be rewritten as follows.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The partial derivative may then be determined by applying standard derivative procedures to $Rz_{k}$ and then simplifying.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Since the only frequencies of relevance are the frequencies at the constriction point and the $i=2{\text{ to }}N_{Rz}$ roots of $|(dK(s)/ds)_{num}|$ , the Jacobian matrix may be constructed as follows.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Where $\omega _{1}$ is the constriction limit frequency, and $\omega _{(i>1)}$ are the magnitude of the roots of the remaining pass band minima, $|dK(s)/ds)_{num}|$ , and $Rz_{k}$ are the reflection zeros.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Convergence is achieved when the sum of all $\sum _{k=1}^{N_{Rz}}|\Delta _{k}|<\delta$ and $\delta$ is sufficiently small for the application, typically between 1.e-05 and 1.e-16.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] For larger filters, it may be necessary to restrict the size of each $\Delta _{k}$ to prevent excessive swings early in the convergence, and to restrict the size of each $Rz_{k+1}$ to keep their values inside the constricted ripple range during convergence.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Design a 7 pole Chebyshev filter with a 1 dB equi-ripple pass band constricted to 55% of the pass band.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Repeat steps 3 through 8 until the application convergence criteria, $\sum _{k=1}^{N_{Rz}}|\Delta _{k}|<\delta _{min}$ , has been met, which for this example is chosen to be 1.e-12.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] When amplitude normalized such that $|K(j)|=1$ , the constructed $K(s)$ is shown below.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The synthesis process may be validated by doing a quick check of $|G(j\omega _{k})|$ for each $\omega _{k}$ from step 3 to insure a 1 dB attenuation at those frequencies, and that the cut-off attenuation at $\omega =1$ is also 1dB.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The summary of the computation below validates the example synthesis process.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The final magnitude frequency response of the forward transfer function, $|G(jw)|$ , is shown below.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Standard low pass Inverse Chebyshev filter design creates an equi-ripple stop band beginning from a normalized value of 1 rad/sec to $\infty$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] However, some design requirements do not need an equi-ripple pass band at the high frequencies.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] A standard full-equi-ripple Inverse Chebyshev filter for this application would result in an over designed filter.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Constricting the equi-ripple to a defined percentage of the stop band creates a more efficient design, reducing the size of the filter and potentially eliminating one or two components, which is useful in maximizing board space efficiency and minimizing production costs for mass produced items.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Inverse Chebyshev filters with constricted stop band ripple are synthesized in exactly the same process as standard a inverse Chebyshev.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] A constricted ripple Chebyshev is designed with an inverted $\varepsilon$ , $\varepsilon ^{2}=1/(10^{(\gamma /10)}-1)$ where $\gamma$ is the stop band attenuation in dB, the poles and zeros of the designed constricted ripple Chebyshev filter are inverted, and the cut-off attenuation is set.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Since standard Chebyshev equations will not work with constricted ripple design, the cut-off attenuation must be set using the process described in the Elliptic Hourglass design.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Below are the |S11| and |S12| scattering parameters for a 7 pole constricted ripple Inverse Chebyshev filter with 3dB cut-off attenuation.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The constricted ripple example above is intentionally kept simple by keeping the cut-off attenuation equal to the pass band ripple attenuation, omitting optional transmission zeros, and using an odd order that does not potentially require even order modification.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] When including stop band transmission zeros, it is import to remember that the roots of $dK(s)/ds)_{num}$ will include stop band maxima with $\omega >1$ .
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] These roots should not be included in the pass band minima used in the computations..
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Since $\varepsilon ^{2}$ may be used to set the cut-off attenuation in $G(s)$ , the step 5 $K(s)$ target values may be made with respect to 1.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The target values in step 5 may be calculated using the expression for $|K(j\omega )|$ obtainable from the equations above.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] Consider a filter design of %constriction = 55, order = 8, single transmission zero at 1.1, pass band ripple attenuation = 0.043648054 (equivalent of S12 = 20dB attenuation based on the relation $|S_{11}|^{2}+|S_{12}|^{2}=1$ for lossless networks), and pass band cut-off attenuation = 20dB.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] The target value in step 5 is .01010101, and the $\varepsilon ^{2}$ to compute $G(s)$ is 99.
[src:rf-filters/chebyshev-filter-p02] When complete, the characteristic polynomials , $K(s)$ , and forward transfer function, $G(s)$ , are below.
