[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] In signal processing, a **comb filter** is a filter implemented by adding a delayed version of a signal to itself, causing constructive and destructive interference.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The frequency response of a comb filter consists of a series of regularly spaced notches in between regularly spaced *peaks* (sometimes called *teeth*), giving the appearance of a comb.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Comb filters exist in two forms, *feedforward* and *feedback*, which refer to the direction in which signals are delayed before they are added to the input.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Comb filters may be implemented in discrete time or continuous time forms, which are very similar.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] In acoustics, comb filtering can arise as an unwanted artifact.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] For instance, two loudspeakers playing the same signal at different distances from the listener create a comb filtering effect on the audio.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] In any enclosed space, listeners hear a mixture of direct sound and reflected sound.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The reflected sound takes a longer, delayed path compared to the direct sound, and a comb filter is created where the two mix at the listener.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Similarly, comb filtering may result from mono mixing of multiple mics, hence the 3:1 rule of thumb that neighboring mics should be separated at least three times the distance from its source to the mic.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] where K is the delay length (measured in samples), and *α* is a scaling factor applied to the delayed signal.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The frequency response of a discrete-time system expressed in the *z*-domain is obtained by substitution $z=e^{j\omega },$ where j is the imaginary unit and $\omega$ is angular frequency.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Often of interest is the *magnitude* response, which ignores phase.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The $(1+\alpha ^{2})$ term is constant, whereas the $2\alpha \cos(\omega K)$ term varies periodically.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Hence, the magnitude response of the comb filter is periodic.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The feedforward comb filter is one of the simplest finite impulse response filters.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Its response is simply the initial impulse with a second impulse after the delay.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] the numerator is equal to zero whenever *zK* = −*α*.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] This has *K* solutions, equally spaced around a circle in the complex plane; these are the zeros of the transfer function.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The denominator is zero at *zK* = 0, giving *K* poles at *z* = 0.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] This leads to a pole–zero plot like the ones shown.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Again, the response is periodic, as the graphs demonstrate.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The feedback comb filter is a simple type of infinite impulse response filter.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] If stable, the response simply consists of a repeating series of impulses decreasing in amplitude over time.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] This time, the numerator is zero at *zK* = 0, giving *K* zeros at *z* = 0.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The denominator is equal to zero whenever *zK* = *α*.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] This has *K* solutions, equally spaced around a circle in the complex plane; these are the poles of the transfer function.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] This leads to a pole–zero plot like the ones shown below.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Comb filters may also be implemented in continuous time, which can be expressed in the Laplace domain as a function of the complex frequency domain parameter $s=\sigma +j\omega$ analogous to the z domain.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Analog circuits use some form of analog delay line for the delay element.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] Continuous-time implementations share all the properties of the respective discrete-time implementations.
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] where *τ* is the delay (measured in seconds).
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The feedforward form consists of an infinite number of zeros spaced along the jω axis (which corresponds to the Fourier domain).
[src:rf-filters/combline-filter] The feedback form consists of an infinite number of poles spaced along the jω axis.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A **distributed-element filter** is an electronic filter in which capacitance, inductance, and resistance (the elements of the circuit) are not localised in discrete capacitors, inductors, and resistors as they are in conventional filters.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Its purpose is to allow a range of signal frequencies to pass, but to block others.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Conventional filters are constructed from inductors and capacitors, and the circuits so built are described by the lumped element model, which considers each element to be "lumped together" at one place.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] That model is conceptually simple, but it becomes increasingly unreliable as the frequency of the signal increases, or equivalently as the wavelength decreases.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The distributed-element model applies at all frequencies, and is used in transmission-line theory; many distributed-element components are made of short lengths of transmission line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] In the distributed view of circuits, the elements are distributed along the length of conductors and are inextricably mixed together.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The filter design is usually concerned only with inductance and capacitance, but because of this mixing of elements they cannot be treated as separate "lumped" capacitors and inductors.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] There is no precise frequency above which distributed element filters must be used but they are especially associated with the microwave band (wavelength less than one metre).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Distributed-element filters are used in many of the same applications as lumped element filters, such as selectivity of radio channel, bandlimiting of noise and multiplexing of many signals into one channel.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Distributed-element filters may be constructed to have any of the bandforms possible with lumped elements (low-pass, band-pass, etc.) with the exception of high-pass, which is usually only approximated.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] All filter classes used in lumped element designs (Butterworth, Chebyshev, etc.) can be implemented using a distributed-element approach.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] There are many component forms used to construct distributed-element filters, but all have the common property of causing a discontinuity on the transmission line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] These discontinuities present a reactive impedance to a wavefront travelling down the line, and these reactances can be chosen by design to serve as approximations for lumped inductors, capacitors or resonators, as required by the filter.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The development of distributed-element filters was spurred on by the military need for radar and electronic counter measures during World War II.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Lumped element analogue filters had long before been developed but these new military systems operated at microwave frequencies and new filter designs were required.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] When the war ended, the technology found applications in the microwave links used by telephone companies and other organisations with large fixed-communication networks, such as television broadcasters.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Nowadays the technology can be found in several mass-produced consumer items, such as the converters (figure 1 shows an example) used with satellite television dishes.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Distributed-element filters are mostly used at frequencies above the VHF (Very High Frequency) band (30 to 300 MHz).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] At these frequencies, the physical length of passive components is a significant fraction of the wavelength of the operating frequency, and it becomes difficult to use the conventional lumped element model.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The exact point at which distributed-element modelling becomes necessary depends on the particular design under consideration.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A common rule of thumb is to apply distributed-element modelling when component dimensions are larger than 0.1λ.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The increasing miniaturisation of electronics has meant that circuit designs are becoming ever smaller compared to λ.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The frequencies beyond which a distributed-element approach to filter design becomes necessary are becoming ever higher as a result of these advances.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] On the other hand, antenna structure dimensions are usually comparable to λ in all frequency bands and require the distributed-element model.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The most noticeable difference in behaviour between a distributed-element filter and its lumped-element approximation is that the former will have multiple passband replicas of the lumped-element prototype passband, because transmission-line transfer characteristics repeat at harmonic intervals.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] These spurious passbands are undesirable in most cases.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] For clarity of presentation, the diagrams in this article are drawn with the components implemented in stripline format.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This does not imply an industry preference, although planar transmission line formats (that is, formats where conductors consist of flat strips) are popular because they can be implemented using established printed circuit board manufacturing techniques.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The structures shown can also be implemented using microstrip or buried stripline techniques (with suitable adjustments to dimensions) and can be adapted to coaxial cables, twin leads and waveguides, although some structures are more suitable for some implementations than others.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The open wire implementations, for instance, of a number of structures are shown in the second column of figure 3 and open wire equivalents can be found for most other stripline structures.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Planar transmission lines are also used in integrated circuit designs.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Development of distributed-element filters began in the years before World War II.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Mason founded the field of distributed-element circuits.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A major paper on the subject was published by Mason and Sykes in 1937.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Mason had filed a patent much earlier, in 1927, and that patent may contain the first published electrical design which moves away from a lumped element analysis.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Mason and Sykes' work was focused on the formats of coaxial cable and balanced pairs of wires – the planar technologies were not yet in use.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Much development was carried out during the war years driven by the filtering needs of radar and electronic counter-measures.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A good deal of this was at the MIT Radiation Laboratory, but other laboratories in the US and the UK were also involved.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Some important advances in network theory were needed before filters could be advanced beyond wartime designs.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] One of these was the commensurate line theory of Paul Richards.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Commensurate lines are networks in which all the elements are the same length (or in some cases multiples of the unit length), although they may differ in other dimensions to give different characteristic impedances.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Richards' transformation allows a lumped element design to be taken "as is" and transformed directly into a distributed-element design using a very simple transform equation.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The difficulty with Richards' transformation from the point of view of building practical filters was that the resulting distributed-element design invariably included series connected elements.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This was not possible to implement in planar technologies and was often inconvenient in other technologies.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Kuroda who used impedance transformers to eliminate the series elements.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] He published a set of transformations known as Kuroda's identities in 1955, but his work was written in Japanese and it was several years before his ideas were incorporated into the English-language literature.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Following the war, one important research avenue was trying to increase the design bandwidth of wide-band filters.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The approach used at the time (and still in use today) was to start with a lumped element prototype filter and through various transformations arrive at the desired filter in a distributed-element form.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This approach appeared to be stuck at a minimum *Q* of five (see Band-pass filters below for an explanation of *Q*).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] In 1957, Leo Young at Stanford Research Institute published a method for designing filters which *started* with a distributed-element prototype.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This prototype was based on quarter wave impedance transformers and was able to produce designs with bandwidths up to an octave, corresponding to a *Q* of about 1.3.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Some of Young's procedures in that paper were empirical, but later, exact solutions were published.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Young's paper specifically addresses directly coupled cavity resonators, but the procedure can equally be applied to other directly coupled resonator types, such as those found in modern planar technologies and illustrated in this article.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The capacitive gap filter (figure 8) and the parallel-coupled lines filter (figure 9) are examples of directly coupled resonators.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The introduction of printed planar technologies greatly simplified the manufacture of many microwave components including filters, and microwave integrated circuits then became possible.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] It is not known when planar transmission lines originated, but experiments using them were recorded as early as 1936.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The inventor of printed stripline, however, is known; this was Robert M.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This caught on rapidly, and Barrett's *stripline* soon had fierce commercial competition from rival planar formats, especially *triplate* and *microstrip*.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The generic term *stripline* in modern usage usually refers to the form then known as *triplate*.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Early stripline directly coupled resonator filters were end-coupled, but the length was reduced and the compactness successively increased with the introduction of parallel-coupled line filters, interdigital filters, and comb-line filters.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Much of this work was published by the group at Stanford led by George Matthaei, and also including Leo Young mentioned above, in a landmark book which still today serves as a reference for circuit designers.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The hairpin filter was first described in 1972.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] By the 1970s, most of the filter topologies in common use today had been described.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] More recent research has concentrated on new or variant mathematical classes of the filters, such as pseudo-elliptic, while still using the same basic topologies, or with alternative implementation technologies such as suspended stripline and finline.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The initial non-military application of distributed-element filters was in the microwave links used by telecommunications companies to provide the backbone of their networks.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] These links were also used by other industries with large, fixed networks, notably television broadcasters.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Such applications were part of large capital investment programs.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] However, mass-production manufacturing made the technology cheap enough to incorporate in domestic satellite television systems.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] An emerging application is in superconducting filters for use in the cellular base stations operated by mobile phone companies.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The simplest structure that can be implemented is a step in the characteristic impedance of the line, which introduces a discontinuity in the transmission characteristics.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This is done in planar technologies by a change in the width of the transmission line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Figure 4(a) shows a step up in impedance (narrower lines have higher impedance).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A step down in impedance would be the mirror image of figure 4(a).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The discontinuity can be represented approximately as a series inductor, or more exactly, as a low-pass T circuit as shown in figure 4(a).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Multiple discontinuities are often coupled together with impedance transformers to produce a filter of higher order.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] These impedance transformers can be just a short (often λ/4) length of transmission line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] These composite structures can implement any of the filter families (Butterworth, Chebyshev, etc.) by approximating the rational transfer function of the corresponding lumped element filter.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This correspondence is not exact since distributed-element circuits cannot be rational and is the root reason for the divergence of lumped element and distributed-element behaviour.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Impedance transformers are also used in hybrid mixtures of lumped and distributed-element filters (the so-called semi-lumped structures).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Another very common component of distributed-element filters is the stub.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Over a narrow range of frequencies, a stub can be used as a capacitor or an inductor (its impedance is determined by its length) but over a wide band it behaves as a resonator.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Short-circuit, nominally quarter-wavelength stubs (figure 3(a)) behave as shunt LC antiresonators, and an open-circuit nominally quarter-wavelength stub (figure 3(b)) behaves as a series LC resonator.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Stubs can also be used in conjunction with impedance transformers to build more complex filters and, as would be expected from their resonant nature, are most useful in band-pass applications.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A helical resonator is similar to a stub, in that it requires a distributed-element model to represent it, but is actually built using lumped elements.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] They are built in a non-planar format and consist of a coil of wire, on a former and core, and connected only at one end.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The device is usually in a shielded can with a hole in the top for adjusting the core.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] It will often look physically very similar to the lumped LC resonators used for a similar purpose.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] They are most useful in the upper VHF and lower UHF bands whereas stubs are more often applied in the higher UHF and SHF bands.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Coupled lines (figures 3(c-e)) can also be used as filter elements; like stubs, they can act as resonators and likewise be terminated short-circuit or open-circuit.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Coupled lines tend to be preferred in planar technologies, where they are easy to implement, whereas stubs tend to be preferred elsewhere.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Implementing a true open circuit in planar technology is not feasible because of the dielectric effect of the substrate which will always ensure that the equivalent circuit contains a shunt capacitance.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Despite this, open circuits are often used in planar formats in preference to short circuits because they are easier to implement.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Numerous element types can be classified as coupled lines and a selection of the more common ones is shown in the figures.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Some common structures are shown in figures 3 and 4, along with their lumped-element counterparts.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] These lumped-element approximations are not to be taken as equivalent circuits but rather as a guide to the behaviour of the distributed elements over a certain frequency range.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Figures 3(a) and 3(b) show a short-circuit and open-circuit stub, respectively.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] When the stub length is λ/4, these behave, respectively, as anti-resonators and resonators and are therefore useful, respectively, as elements in band-pass and band-stop filters.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Figure 3(c) shows a short-circuited line coupled to the main line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This also behaves as a resonator, but is commonly used in low-pass filter applications with the resonant frequency well outside the band of interest.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Figures 3(d) and 3(e) show coupled line structures which are both useful in band-pass filters.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The structures of figures 3(c) and 3(e) have equivalent circuits involving stubs placed in series with the line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Such a topology is straightforward to implement in open-wire circuits but not with a planar technology.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] These two structures are therefore useful for implementing an equivalent series element.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A low-pass filter can be implemented quite directly from a ladder topology lumped-element prototype with the stepped impedance filter shown in figure 5.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This is also called a *cascaded lines* design.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The filter consists of alternating sections of high-impedance and low-impedance lines which correspond to the series inductors and shunt capacitors in the lumped-element implementation.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Low-pass filters are commonly used to feed direct current (DC) bias to active components.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Filters intended for this application are sometimes referred to as *chokes*.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Additional sections may be added as required for the performance of the filter just as they would for the lumped-element counterpart.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] As well as the planar form shown, this structure is particularly well suited for coaxial implementations with alternating discs of metal and insulator being threaded on to the central conductor.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A more complex example of stepped impedance design is presented in figure 6.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Again, narrow lines are used to implement inductors and wide lines correspond to capacitors, but in this case, the lumped-element counterpart has resonators connected in shunt across the main line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This topology can be used to design elliptical filters or Chebyshev filters with poles of attenuation in the stopband.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] However, calculating component values for these structures is an involved process and has led to designers often choosing to implement them as m-derived filters instead, which perform well and are much easier to calculate.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The purpose of incorporating resonators is to improve the stopband rejection.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] However, beyond the resonant frequency of the highest frequency resonator, the stopband rejection starts to deteriorate as the resonators are moving towards open-circuit.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] For this reason, filters built to this design often have an additional single stepped-impedance capacitor as the final element of the filter.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This also ensures good rejection at high frequency.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Another common low-pass design technique is to implement the shunt capacitors as stubs with the resonant frequency set above the operating frequency so that the stub impedance is capacitive in the passband.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This implementation has a lumped-element counterpart of a general form similar to the filter of figure 6.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Where space allows, the stubs may be set on alternate sides of the main line as shown in figure 7(a).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The purpose of this is to prevent coupling between adjacent stubs which detracts from the filter performance by altering the frequency response.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] However, a structure with all the stubs on the same side is still a valid design.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] If the stub is required to be a very low impedance line, the stub may be inconveniently wide.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] In these cases, a possible solution is to connect two narrower stubs in parallel.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] That is, each stub position has a stub on *both sides* of the line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A drawback of this topology is that additional transverse resonant modes are possible along the λ/2 length of line formed by the two stubs together.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] For a choke design, the requirement is simply to make the capacitance as large as possible, for which the maximum stub width of λ/4 may be used with stubs in parallel on both sides of the main line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The resulting filter looks rather similar to the stepped impedance filter of figure 5, but has been designed on completely different principles.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A difficulty with using stubs this wide is that the point at which they are connected to the main line is ill-defined.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A stub that is narrow in comparison to λ can be taken as being connected on its centre-line and calculations based on that assumption will accurately predict filter response.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] For a wide stub, however, calculations that assume the side branch is connected at a definite point on the main line leads to inaccuracies as this is no longer a good model of the transmission pattern.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] One solution to this difficulty is to use radial stubs instead of linear stubs.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A pair of radial stubs in parallel (one on either side of the main line) is called a butterfly stub (see figure 7(b)).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A group of three radial stubs in parallel, which can be achieved at the end of a line, is called a clover-leaf stub.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A band-pass filter can be constructed using any elements that can resonate.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Filters using stubs can clearly be made band-pass; numerous other structures are possible and some are presented below.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] An important parameter when discussing band-pass filters is the fractional bandwidth.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This is defined as the ratio of the bandwidth to the geometric centre frequency.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The inverse of this quantity is called the Q-factor, *Q*.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The capacitive gap structure consists of sections of line about λ/2 in length which act as resonators and are coupled "end-on" by gaps in the transmission line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] It is particularly suitable for planar formats, is easily implemented with printed circuit technology and has the advantage of taking up no more space than a plain transmission line would.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The limitation of this topology is that performance (particularly insertion loss) deteriorates with increasing fractional bandwidth, and acceptable results are not obtained with a *Q* less than about 5.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A further difficulty with producing low-*Q* designs is that the gap width is required to be smaller for wider fractional bandwidths.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The minimum width of gaps, like the minimum width of tracks, is limited by the resolution of the printing technology.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Parallel-coupled lines is another popular topology for printed boards, for which open-circuit lines are the simplest to implement since the manufacturing consists of nothing more than the printed track.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The design consists of a row of parallel λ/2 resonators, but coupling over only λ/4 to each of the neighbouring resonators, so forming a staggered line as shown in figure 9.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Wider fractional bandwidths are possible with this filter than with the capacitive gap filter, but a similar problem arises on printed boards as dielectric loss reduces the *Q*.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Lower-*Q* lines require tighter coupling and smaller gaps between them which is limited by the accuracy of the printing process.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] One solution to this problem is to print the track on multiple layers with adjacent lines overlapping but not in contact because they are on different layers.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] In this way, the lines can be coupled across their width, which results in much stronger coupling than when they are edge-to-edge, and a larger gap becomes possible for the same performance.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] For other (non-printed) technologies, short-circuit lines may be preferred since the short-circuit provides a mechanical attachment point for the line and *Q*-reducing dielectric insulators are not required for mechanical support.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Other than for mechanical and assembly reasons, there is little preference for open-circuit over short-circuit coupled lines.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Both structures can realize the same range of filter implementations with the same electrical performance.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Both types of parallel-coupled filters, in theory, do not have spurious passbands at twice the centre frequency as seen in many other filter topologies (e.g., stubs).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] However, suppression of this spurious passband requires perfect tuning of the coupled lines which is not realized in practice, so there is inevitably some residual spurious passband at this frequency.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The hairpin filter is another structure that uses parallel-coupled lines.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] In this case, each pair of parallel-coupled lines is connected to the next pair by a short link.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The "U" shapes so formed give rise to the name *hairpin filter*.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] In some designs the link can be longer, giving a wide hairpin with λ/4 impedance transformer action between sections.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The angled bends seen in figure 10 are common to stripline designs and represent a compromise between a sharp right angle, which produces a large discontinuity, and a smooth bend, which takes up more board area which can be severely limited in some products.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Such bends are often seen in long stubs where they could not otherwise be fitted into the space available.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The lumped-element equivalent circuit of this kind of discontinuity is similar to a stepped-impedance discontinuity.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Examples of such stubs can be seen on the bias inputs to several components in the photograph at the top of the article.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Interdigital filters are another form of coupled-line filter.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Each section of line is about λ/4 in length and is terminated in a short-circuit at one end only, the other end being left open-circuit.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The end which is short-circuited alternates on each line section.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This topology is straightforward to implement in planar technologies, but also particularly lends itself to a mechanical assembly of lines fixed inside a metal case.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The lines can be either circular rods or rectangular bars, and interfacing to a coaxial format line is easy.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] As with the parallel-coupled line filter, the advantage of a mechanical arrangement that does not require insulators for support is that dielectric losses are eliminated.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The spacing requirement between lines is not as stringent as in the parallel line structure; as such, higher fractional bandwidths can be achieved, and *Q* values as low as 1.4 are possible.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The comb-line filter is similar to the interdigital filter in that it lends itself to mechanical assembly in a metal case without dielectric support.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] In the case of the comb-line, all the lines are short-circuited at the same end rather than alternate ends.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The other ends are terminated in capacitors to ground, and the design is consequently classified as semi-lumped.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The chief advantage of this design is that the upper stopband can be made very wide, that is, free of spurious passbands at all frequencies of interest.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] As mentioned above, stubs lend themselves to band-pass designs.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] General forms of these are similar to stub low-pass filters except that the main line is no longer a narrow high impedance line.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Designers have many different topologies of stub filters to choose from, some of which produce identical responses.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] An example stub filter is shown in figure 12; it consists of a row of λ/4 short-circuit stubs coupled together by λ/4 impedance transformers.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The stubs in the body of the filter are double paralleled stubs while the stubs on the end sections are only singles, an arrangement that has impedance matching advantages.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The impedance transformers have the effect of transforming the row of shunt anti-resonators into a ladder of series resonators and shunt anti-resonators.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] A filter with similar properties can be constructed with λ/4 open-circuit stubs placed in series with the line and coupled together with λ/4 impedance transformers, although this structure is not possible in planar technologies.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Yet another structure available is λ/2 open-circuit stubs across the line coupled with λ/4 impedance transformers.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] This topology has both low-pass and band-pass characteristics.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Because it will pass DC, it is possible to transmit biasing voltages to active components without the need for blocking capacitors.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Also, since short-circuit links are not required, no assembly operations other than the board printing are required when implemented as stripline.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Konishi describes a wideband 12 GHz band-pass filter, which uses 60° butterfly stubs and also has a low-pass response (short-circuit stubs are required to prevent such a response).
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] As is often the case with distributed-element filters, the bandform into which the filter is classified largely depends on which bands are desired and which are considered to be spurious.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Genuine high-pass filters are difficult, if not impossible, to implement with distributed elements.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] The usual design approach is to start with a band-pass design, but make the upper stopband occur at a frequency that is so high as to be of no interest.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Such filters are described as pseudo-high-pass and the upper stopband is described as a vestigial stopband.
[src:rf-filters/distributed-element-filter] Even structures that seem to have an "obvious" high-pass topology, such as the capacitive gap filter of figure 8, turn out to be band-pass when their behaviour for very short wavelengths is considered.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Electronic filters remove unwanted frequency components from the applied signal, enhance wanted ones, or both.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The most common types of electronic filters are linear filters, regardless of other aspects of their design.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] See the article on linear filters for details on their design and analysis.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The oldest forms of electronic filters are passive analog linear filters, constructed using only resistors and capacitors or resistors and inductors.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] These are known as RC and RL single-pole filters respectively.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] However, these simple filters have very limited uses.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Multipole LC filters provide greater control of response form, bandwidth and transition bands.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The first of these filters was the constant k filter, invented by George Campbell in 1910.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Campbell's filter was a ladder network based on transmission line theory.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Together with improved filters by Otto Zobel and others, these filters are known as image parameter filters.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] A major step forward was taken by Wilhelm Cauer who founded the field of network synthesis around the time of World War II.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Cauer's theory allowed filters to be constructed that precisely followed some prescribed frequency function.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Passive implementations of linear filters are based on combinations of resistors (R), inductors (L) and capacitors (C).
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] These types are collectively known as *passive filters*, because they do not depend upon an external power supply and they do not contain active components such as transistors.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Inductors block high-frequency signals and conduct low-frequency signals, while capacitors do the reverse.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] A filter in which the signal passes through an inductor, or in which a capacitor provides a path to ground, presents less attenuation to low-frequency signals than high-frequency signals and is therefore a *low-pass filter*.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] If the signal passes through a capacitor, or has a path to ground through an inductor, then the filter presents less attenuation to high-frequency signals than low-frequency signals and therefore is a *high-pass filter*.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Resistors on their own have no frequency-selective properties, but are added to inductors and capacitors to determine the *time-constants* of the circuit, and therefore the frequencies to which it responds.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The inductors and capacitors are the reactive elements of the filter.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The number of elements determines the order of the filter.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] In this context, an LC tuned circuit being used in a band-pass or band-stop filter is considered a single element even though it consists of two components.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] At high frequencies (above about 100 megahertz), sometimes the inductors consist of single loops or strips of sheet metal, and the capacitors consist of adjacent strips of metal.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] These inductive or capacitive pieces of metal are called stubs.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The simplest passive filters, RC and RL filters, include only one reactive element, except for the hybrid LC filter, which is characterized by inductance and capacitance integrated in one element.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] An L filter consists of two reactive elements, one in series and one in parallel.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Three-element filters can have a 'T' or 'π' topology and in either geometries, a low-pass, high-pass, band-pass, or band-stop characteristic is possible.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The components can be chosen symmetric or not, depending on the required frequency characteristics.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The high-pass T filter in the illustration, has a very low impedance at high frequencies, and a very high impedance at low frequencies.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] That means that it can be inserted in a transmission line, resulting in the high frequencies being passed and low frequencies being reflected.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Likewise, for the illustrated low-pass π filter, the circuit can be connected to a transmission line, transmitting low frequencies and reflecting high frequencies.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Using m-derived filter sections with correct termination impedances, the input impedance can be reasonably constant in the pass band.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Multiple-element filtration are usually constructed as a ladder network.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] These can be seen as a continuation of the L,T and π designs of filters.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] More elements are needed when it is desired to improve some parameter of the filter such as stop-band rejection or slope of transition from pass-band to stop-band.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Reflectionless filters are passive structures that in principle have identically zero reflection coefficient at all frequencies.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Such structures may be synthesized with lumped inductors, capacitors, and resistors, or by transmission lines and resistors.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Active filters are implemented using a combination of passive and active (amplifying) components, and require an outside power source.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Operational amplifiers are frequently used in active filter designs.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] These can have high Q factor, and can achieve resonance without the use of inductors.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] However, their upper frequency limit is limited by the bandwidth of the amplifiers.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] There are many filter technologies other than lumped component electronics.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] These include digital filters, crystal filters, mechanical filters, surface acoustic wave (SAW) filters, thin-film bulk acoustic resonator (TFBAR, FBAR) based filters, garnet filters, and atomic filters (used in atomic clocks).
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The transfer function of all linear time-invariant filters, when constructed of lumped components (as opposed to distributed components such as transmission lines), will be the ratio of two polynomials in s , i.e. a rational function of $\ s$ .
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The order of the transfer function will be the highest power of $\ s$ encountered in either the numerator or the denominator.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Electronic filters can be classified by the technology used to implement them.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Filters using passive filter and active filter technology can be further classified by the particular electronic filter topology used to implement them.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Any given filter transfer function may be implemented in any electronic filter topology.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Historically, linear analog filter design has evolved through three major approaches.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The oldest designs are simple circuits where the main design criterion was the Q factor of the circuit.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] This reflected the radio receiver application of filtering as Q was a measure of the frequency selectivity of a tuning circuit.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] From the 1920s filters began to be designed from the image point of view, mostly being driven by the requirements of telecommunications.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] After World War II the dominant methodology was network synthesis.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The higher mathematics used originally required extensive tables of polynomial coefficient values to be published but modern computer resources have made that unnecessary.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Low order filters can be designed by directly applying basic circuit laws such as Kirchhoff's laws to obtain the transfer function.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] This kind of analysis is usually only carried out for simple filters of 1st or 2nd order.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] This approach analyses the filter sections from the point of view of the filter being in an infinite chain of identical sections.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] It has the advantages of simplicity of approach and the ability to easily extend to higher orders.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] It has the disadvantage that accuracy of predicted responses relies on filter terminations in the image impedance, which is usually not the case.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The network synthesis approach starts with a required transfer function and then expresses that as a polynomial equation of the input impedance of the filter.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The actual element values of the filter are obtained by continued-fraction or partial-fraction expansions of this polynomial.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Unlike the image method, there is no need for impedance matching networks at the terminations as the effects of the terminating resistors are included in the analysis from the start.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] Here is an image comparing Butterworth, Chebyshev, and elliptic filters.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The filters in this illustration are all fifth-order low-pass filters.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] The particular implementation – analog or digital, passive or active – makes no difference; their output would be the same.
[src:rf-filters/electronic-filter] As is clear from the image, elliptic filters are sharper than all the others, but they show ripples on the whole bandwidth.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] An **elliptic filter** (also known as a **Cauer filter**, named after Wilhelm Cauer, or as a **Zolotarev filter**, after Yegor Zolotarev) is a signal processing filter with equalized ripple (equiripple) behavior in both the passband and the stopband.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The amount of ripple in each band is independently adjustable, and no other filter of equal order can have a faster transition in gain between the passband and the stopband, for the given values of ripple (whether the ripple is equalized or not).
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Alternatively, one may give up the ability to adjust independently the passband and stopband ripple, and instead design a filter which is maximally insensitive to component variations.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] As the ripple in the stopband approaches zero, the filter becomes a type I Chebyshev filter.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] As the ripple in the passband approaches zero, the filter becomes a type II Chebyshev filter and finally, as both ripple values approach zero, the filter becomes a Butterworth filter.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The value of the ripple factor specifies the passband ripple, while the combination of the ripple factor and the selectivity factor specify the stopband ripple.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The zeroes of the gain of an elliptic filter will coincide with the poles of the elliptic rational function, which are derived in the article on elliptic rational functions.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The poles of the gain of an elliptic filter may be derived in a manner very similar to the derivation of the poles of the gain of a type I Chebyshev filter.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] For simplicity, assume that the cutoff frequency is equal to unity.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The poles $(\omega _{pm})$ of the gain of the elliptic filter will be the zeroes of the denominator of the gain.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] where the multiple values of the inverse cd() function are made explicit using the integer index *m*.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] As is the case for the Chebyshev polynomials, this may be expressed in explicitly complex form (Lutovac & et al.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] where $\zeta _{n}$ is a function of $n,\,\epsilon$ and $\xi$ and $x_{m}$ are the zeroes of the elliptic rational function. $\zeta _{n}$ is expressible for all *n* in terms of Jacobi elliptic functions, or algebraically for some orders, especially orders 1,2, and 3.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The algebraic expression for $\zeta _{3}$ is rather involved (See Lutovac & et al.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Elliptic filters are generally specified by requiring a particular value for the passband ripple, αp, stopband ripple, αs, and the sharpness of the cutoff.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] These specify a minimum order n for the rational elliptic function describing the filter behavior.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] This sensitivity is inversely proportional to the quality factor (Q-factor) of the poles of the filter transfer function.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] and is a measure of the influence of the pole on the gain function.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] This results in a filter which is maximally insensitive to component variations, but the ability to independently specify the passband and stopband ripples will be lost.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] For such filters, as the order increases, the ripple in both bands will decrease and the rate of cutoff will increase.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] If one decides to use a minimum-Q elliptic filter in order to achieve a particular minimum ripple in the filter bands along with a particular rate of cutoff, the order needed will generally be greater than the order one would otherwise need without the minimum-Q restriction.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] An image of the absolute value of the gain will look very much like the image in the previous section, except that the poles are arranged in a circle rather than an ellipse.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] They will not be evenly spaced and there will be zeroes on the ω axis, unlike the Butterworth filter, whose poles are arranged in an evenly spaced circle with no zeroes.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Elliptic filter stop bands are essentially Chebyshev filters with transmission zeros where the transmission zeros are arranged in a manner that yields an equi-ripple stop band.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The scaling factor used, $\Omega _{c}$ , is the stop band to pass band cutoff frequency ratios and is also known as the inverse of the "selectivity factor".
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Since Elliptic designs are generally specified from the stop band attenuation requirements, $\Omega _{c}$ , may be derived from the equations that establish the minimum order, n, above.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] the $\omega _{s}/\omega _{p}$ ratio, $\Omega _{c}$ may be derived by working the minimum order, *n*, problem above backwards from *n* to find $\Omega _{c}$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Design an Elliptic filter with a pass band ripple of 1 dB from 0 to 1 rad/sec and a stop band ripple of 40 dB from at least 1.25 rad/sec to $\infty$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Applying the calculations above for the value for n prior to applying the ***ceil()*** function, n is found to be 4.83721900 rounded up to the next integer, 5, by applying the ***ceil()*** function, which means a 5 pole Elliptic filter is required to meet the specified design requirements.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Applying the calculations above for $\Omega _{c}$ needed to design a stop band of exactly 40 dB of attenuation, $\Omega _{c}$ is found to be 1.2186824.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The polynomial scaled inversion function may be performed by translating each root, ***s***, to $\Omega _{c}/s$ , which may be easily accomplished by inverting the polynomial and scaling it by $\Omega _{c}$ , as shown.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Repeat steps 2 and 3 until both the pass band and stop band no longer change by any appreciable amount.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Typically, 15 to 25 iterations produce coefficient differences in the order of than 1.e-15.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] To illustrate the steps, the below K(s) equations begin with a standard Chebyshev K(s), then iterate through the process.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Visible differences are seen in the first three iterations.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] By time 18 iterations have been reached, the differences in K(s) become negligible.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Iterations may be discontinued when the change in K(s) coefficients becomes sufficiently small so as to meet design accuracy requirements.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The below K(s) iterations have all been normalized such that $|K(j)|=1$ , however, this step may be postponed until the last iteration, if desired.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] To obtain $G(s)$ from the left half plane, factor the numerator and denominator to obtain the roots using a root finding algorithm.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] This is due to the physical inability to accommodate the even order Chebyshev reflection zeros and transmission zeros that result in the scattering matrix S12 values that exceed the S12 value at $\omega =0$ , and the finite S12 values that exist at $\omega =\infty$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The lowest frequency reflection zero may be found by factoring the $K(s)$ numerator, and the highest frequency transmission zero may be found be factoring the $K(s)$ denominator.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The translate the reflection zeros, the following equation is applied to all poles and zeros of $K(s)$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] While in theory, the translation operations may be performed on either $K(s)$ or $G(s)$ , the reflection zeros must be extracted from $K(s)$ , so it is generally more efficient to perform the translation operations on $K(s)$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] $R_{i}'$ is the mapped zero or pole for the modified even order transfer function.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] $\omega _{LO}$ is the lowest frequency reflection zero in the pass band.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The sign of imaginary component of $R_{i}'$ is determined by the sign of the original $R_{i}$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The translate the transmission zeros, the following equation is applied to all poles and zeros of $K(s)$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] While in theory, the translation operations may be performed on either $K(s)$ or $G(s)$ , if the reflection zeros must be extracted from $K(s)$ , it may be more efficient to perform the translation operations on $K(s)$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] $\omega _{HI}$ is the highest frequency transmission zero in the pass band.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] If operating on $G(s)$ the sign of the real component of $R_{i}'$ must be negative to conform to the left half plane requirement.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] It is important to note that all applications require both pass and stop translations.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Passive network diplexers, for example, only require even order stop band translations, and perform more efficiently with untranslated even order pass bands.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] When $G(s)$ is completed, an equi-ripple transfer function is created with scattering matrix values for S12 of 1 $\omega =0$ and 0 at $\omega =\infty$ , which may be implements with passive equally terminated networks.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The $\Omega _{c}$ and order computation in the Elliptic construction paragraph above are for unmodified Elliptic filters only.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Although even order modifications have no effect on the pass band or stop band attenuation, small errors are to be expected in the order and $\Omega _{c}$ computations.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Therefore, it is important to apply even order modifications after all $K(s)$ iterations complete if it is desired to preserve the pass and stop band attenuations.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] If the even order modified Elliptic function is created from an $\Omega _{c}$ requirement, the actual $\Omega _{c}$ will be slightly larger than the design $\Omega _{c}$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Likewise, an order, ***n***, computation may result in a smaller value than the actual required order.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] An Hourglass filter is a special case of filter where the reflection zeros, are the reciprocal of the transmission zeros about a 3.01 dB normalized cut-off attenuation frequency of 1 rad/sec, resulting all poles of the filter residing on the unit circle.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The Elliptic Hourglass implementation has an advantage over an Inverse Chebyshev filter in that the pass band is flatter, and has an advantage over traditional Elliptic filters in that the group delay has a less sharp peak at the cut-off frequency.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Together with the well known magnitude dB to arithmetic translation, $(S_{ij})_{dB}=20log_{10}(|S_{ij}|_{arith})$ , algebraic manipulation yields the following pass band attenuation calculated requirement.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The result will be polynomials with an attenuation of 3.01 dB at a normalized frequency of 1 rad/sec.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Newton's method or solving the equations directly with a root finding algorithm may be used to determine the 3.01 dB attenuation frequency.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] 2. negate all terms of $s^{n}$ when $(n+2)$ is divisible by 4 .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Convert the desired attenuation in dB, $A_{dB}$ , to a squared arithmetic gain value, $B_{arith}^{2}$ , by using $B_{arith}^{2}=10^{A_{dB}/10}$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Calculate the modified $|G_{2}(s)G_{2}(-s)|$ in Newton's method using the real value, $\omega _{a}$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Calculate the derivative the modified $G_{2}(\omega _{a})G_{2}(-\omega _{a})$ with respect to the real value, $\omega _{a}$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] DO NOT take the absolute value of the derivative.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] using a real value for $\omega _{a}$ with no complex arithmetic needed.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The movement of $\omega _{a}$ should be limited to prevent it from going negative early in the iterations for increased reliability.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] When convergence is complete, $\omega _{a}$ can used for the $\omega _{c}$ that can be used to scale the original $G(s)$ transfer function denominator.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The attenuation of the modified $G(s)$ will then be virtually the exact desired value at 1 rad/sec.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] If performed properly, only a handful of iterations are needed to set the attenuation through a wide range of desired attenuation values for both small and very large order filters.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Since $|G(j\omega _{a})|$ does not contain any phase information, directly factoring the transfer function will not produce usable results.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] However, the transfer function may be modified by multiplying it with $G(-s)$ to eliminate all odd powers of $G(j\omega a)$ , which in turn forces $G(j\omega a)$ to be real at all frequencies, and then finding the frequency that result on the square of the desired attention.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Find the roots of P(S) using a root finding algorithm.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Of the set of roots from above, select the positive imaginary root for all order filters, and positive real root for even order filters for $\omega _{c}$ .
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] Even order Hourglass filters have the same limitations regarding equally terminated passive networks as other Elliptic filters.
[src:rf-filters/elliptic-filter] The same even order modifications that resolve the problem with Elliptic filters also resolve the problem with Hourglass filters.
